08547nam a22011415i 9783110582758DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20182018gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1054880461  a97831105827587 a10.1515/97831105827582doi  a(DE-B1597)490186  a(OCoLC)1037979887  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP305.18.T33bP59 201804a417.222300aLinguistic Taboo Revisited :bNovel Insights from Cognitive Perspectives /ced. by Andrea Pizarro Pedraza. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (XIV, 332 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCognitive Linguistics Research [CLR] ,x1861-4132 ;v6100tFrontmatter -- tForeword -- tTable of contents -- tList of contributing Authors -- tIntroduction -- t1. Lexicon, discourse and cognition: terminological delimitations in the conceptualizations of linguistic taboo -- tPart I: Construal -- t2. The axiological and communicative potential of homosexual-related metaphors -- t3. Metonymy-based euphemisms in war-related speeches by George W. Bush and Barack Obama -- t4. Ambiguity and vagueness as cognitive tools for euphemistic and politically correct speech -- tPart II: Cultural Conceptualization -- t5. Old age revolution in Australian English: Rethinking a taboo concept -- t6. Taboo subjects as insult intensifiers in Egyptian Arabic -- t7. Emotion concepts in context: Figurative conceptualizations of hayâ ‘self-restraint’ in Persian -- t8. A Cognitive Linguistics approach to menstruation as a taboo in Gĩkũyũ -- t9. The socio-cognitive aspects of taboo in two cultures: A case study on Polish and British English -- t10. The influence of conceptual differences on processing taboo metaphors in the foreign language -- tPart III: Cognitive Sociolinguistics -- t11. Why do the Dutch swear with diseases? -- t12. Calling things by their name: Exploring the social meanings in the preference for sexual (in)direct construals -- t13. The perception of the expression of taboos: a sociolinguistic study -- tPart IV: Interdisciplinary Approaches -- t14. Scrupulosity, sexual ruminations and cleaning in Obsessive – Compulsive Disorder -- t15. Swearing as emotion acts -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLinguistic taboo has been relegated for a long time to a peripheral position within Linguistics, due to its social stigmatization and inherent linguistic complexity. Recently, though, there has been a renewed interest in revisiting the phenomenon, especially from cognitive frameworks. This volume is the first collection of papers dealing with linguistic taboo from that perspective. The volume gathers 15 chapters, which provide novel insights into a broad range of taboo phenomena (euphemism, dysphemism, swearing, political correctness, coprolalia, etc.) from the fields of sexuality, diseases, death, war, ageing or religion. With a special focus on lexical semantics, the authors in the volume work within Cognitive Linguistics frameworks such as conceptual metaphor and metonymy, cultural conceptualization or cognitive sociolinguistics, but also at the interface of pragmatics, discourse analysis, applied linguistics, cognitive science or psychiatry. This volume provides theoretical reflections and case studies based on new methods and data from varied languages (English, Spanish, Polish, Dutch, Persian, Gikũyũ and Egyptian Arabic). As such, it moves towards a new generation of linguistic taboo studies.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aEuphemism. 0aTaboo, Linguistic.  aCognitive Linguistics.  aLanguage and Culture.  aLanguage and Society.  aLinguistic Taboo.1 aAllan, Keith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.lo